<h2 id="changing-the-home-chord-for-the-chorus">Changing the home chord for the chorus</h2>
<p>In folk and country tunes there is often a focus of just a few primary chords, often <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">I</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">IV</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">V</code>.  Songs will often make a loop of these primary chords. For the verse sections of the song one of these chords will be chosen as the starting chord. For the chorus one of the other primary chords is chosen as the starting chord. This provides some sense of journey and motion with very little new material. The two sections often end with the same or similar harmonic idea but begin with a different structure. I am curious how this idea can be extended into other kinds of modal writing where there are analagous <a class="internal-link" href="/primary-chords">primary chords</a> to Ionianâ€™s <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">I</code>, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">IV</code>, and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">V</code> chords.</p>

<h3 id="examples">examples:</h3>
<h4 id="sweet-revenge---john-prine">Sweet Revenge - John Prine</h4>
<p>The verse starts on <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">I</code> and the chorus starts on <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">IV</code>
verse: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">I - IV - I - V7 - I - IV - I - V7 - IV - I</code>
chorus: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">IV - I - I - V7 - I - IV - I - V7 - IV - I</code></p>

<h4 id="christmas-in-prison---john-prine">Christmas in Prison - John Prine</h4>
<p>The verse starts on <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">I</code> and the chorus starts on <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">V</code>
verse: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">I - IV - I - V - I - IV - I - V - I</code>
chorus: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">V - IV - I - IV - I - V - I - IV - I - V - I</code></p>
